<section class="section bg-cool" id="why">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <span class="script script-xl" style="color:var(--secondary-text)">Here's Why We Built This</span>
    <h2 class="headline">She didn't open her center to fight with software.</h2>
    <div class="curve curve-left"></div>
    <div class="feature-split" style="gap:3rem;align-items:start">
      <div style="font-size:.92rem;color:var(--text-light);line-height:1.8">
        <p style="margin-bottom:1.2rem">Our first client runs a franchise tutoring center with over 300 students. She got into education for the kids, but found herself spending more time managing broken tools than working with families.</p>
        <p style="margin-bottom:1.2rem">She wasn't on paper. She'd already invested in real platforms: all-in-one marketing tools, funnel builders, CRM systems that promised to handle everything. <span style="background:rgba(224,113,44,.08);color:var(--accent-text);padding:.15rem .5rem;border-radius:4px;font-weight:600">Thousands of dollars</span> across multiple platforms.</p>
        <p style="margin-bottom:1.2rem">But every platform had the same fundamental flaw: <strong style="color:var(--text)">one-to-one data relationships.</strong> One parent email, one child. A mom with three kids needed three separate accounts. That's not how families work. No amount of custom fields could fix a structural data problem.</p>
        <p style="margin-bottom:1.2rem">The marketing tools were great at selling online courses. The CRM systems were built for sales pipelines. None of them understood that a tutoring center has 300 students walking through a physical door. <strong style="color:var(--text)">They were digital-first tools being forced into a physical-operations world.</strong></p>
        <p>So we built it differently. <strong style="color:var(--text)">The Center Book starts with the database:</strong> real multi-to-multi relationships where one parent connects to multiple children, billing and communication contacts are separate, and every piece of the platform reads from the same source of truth.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pain-stack">
        <h3>The problems we kept seeing</h3>
        <div class="pain-item"><div class="pain-item-icon"><i data-lucide="clipboard-list" style="width:16px;height:16px;color:var(--neutral)"></i></div><div class="pain-item-text"><strong>Paper sign-in sheets and manual check-in</strong><span>No instant access to medical alerts or session history</span></div></div>
        <div class="pain-item"><div class="pain-item-icon"><i data-lucide="search" style="width:16px;height:16px;color:var(--neutral)"></i></div><div class="pain-item-text"><strong>No real-time classroom visibility</strong><span>No way to see progress without walking the room</span></div></div>
        <div class="pain-item"><div class="pain-item-icon"><i data-lucide="phone" style="width:16px;height:16px;color:var(--neutral)"></i></div><div class="pain-item-text"><strong>Pickup texts from personal phones</strong><span>No automation, no consent tracking, no records</span></div></div>
        <div class="pain-item"><div class="pain-item-icon"><i data-lucide="archive" style="width:16px;height:16px;color:var(--neutral)"></i></div><div class="pain-item-text"><strong>Student data scattered across systems</strong><span>Some in spreadsheets, some undocumented</span></div></div>
        <div class="pain-item"><div class="pain-item-icon"><i data-lucide="users" style="width:16px;height:16px;color:var(--neutral)"></i></div><div class="pain-item-text"><strong>Every system required one email per child</strong><span>Families forced into duplicate accounts</span></div></div>
        <div style="margin-top:1rem;padding:1rem;border-radius:8px;background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--primary-ultra-light),var(--secondary-ultra-light))">
          <strong style="font-size:.8rem;color:var(--text)">The common thread?</strong><br><span style="font-size:.72rem;color:var(--neutral)">Great educators spending their energy on tools instead of students</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

